1 Clark Gable plays a con man who busts into the life of hard - boiled dame Jean Harlow . He tries to sucker her while she brushes him off with her tough - gal attitude . Despite their cynicism and cons they fall in love . When Gable accidentally kills a man during a sting he runs out leaving loyal Harlow to women 's prison where she discovers she 's pregnant . Anita Loos ' and Howard Emmett Rogers ' writing is excellent throughout with many well - drawn and surprising characters ( including a Jewish socialist woman inmate and a black woman inmate and her preacher father played with hardly a trace of stereotype ) . Gable and Harlow show their mettle as actors adding telling nuances and quirks to their characters that send them beyond the typical Gable and Harlow roles . And the direction is much better than you 'd expect from Sam Wood . One beautiful shot has Harlow being inducted into the prison , then led out into a surprisingly snowy courtyard as the camera tracks after her . This is one of the best of both the " criminals in love " and " women 's prison " genres and has some of the best hard - boiled dialogue ever written .
